(40, 11, 8, 47, 11, 27, 27, 'man clothed in soft raiment', 'Contrast of Clothing and Hardship', 'This connection highlights the contrast between those who wear soft clothing, associated with luxury, and the hardships endured by Paul, including cold and nakedness. Both passages emphasize the differing experiences of comfort and suffering.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 8, 46, 4, 11, 11, 'soft raiment', 'Contrast of Clothing and Condition', 'This connection highlights the contrast between those who wear soft clothing in luxury and those who are described as naked and suffering. Both passages emphasize the disparity between worldly comfort and spiritual hardship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 8, 66, 11, 3, 3, 'a man clothed in soft raiment', 'Contrast of Clothing in Prophecy', 'This connection highlights the contrast between those who wear ''soft raiment'' in luxury and the ''two witnesses'' who are ''clothed in sackcloth'' as a symbol of humility and mourning. Both passages emphasize the significance of clothing in conveying deeper spiritual messages.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 9, 42, 1, 76, 76, 'a prophet? yea, I say unto you, and more than a prophet', 'Connection of Prophetic Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the role of a prophet. Matthew identifies John the Baptist as ''more than a prophet,'' while Luke explicitly calls him ''the prophet of the Highest.'' This connection highlights the significance of prophetic preparation for the Lord.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 9, 40, 14, 5, 5, 'a prophet', 'Connection of Prophetic Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of John the Baptist as a prophet. In Matthew 11:9, Jesus affirms John''s prophetic role, while Matthew 14:5 shows the people''s perception of him as a prophet, influencing Herod''s actions.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 9, 40, 17, 12, 13, 'a prophet? yea, I say unto you', 'John the Baptist as a Prophet', 'Both passages emphasize the prophetic role of John the Baptist. In Matthew 11:9, he is identified as ''more than a prophet,'' while Matthew 17:12-13 directly connects him to Elijah, reinforcing his prophetic significance.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
